{
  "local_port": 51238,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can your remove white underarm stains from shirts?",
  "response": "Removing white underarm stains from shirts can be a bit tricky, but there are several methods you can try to effectively get rid of them:\n\n1. **Baking Soda and Water Paste:**\n   - Mix 3 parts baking soda with 1 part water to form a paste.\n   - Apply the paste to the stained area and let it sit for about 30 minutes.\n   - Gently scrub the area with a soft brush or cloth.\n   - Rinse with cold water and wash the shirt as usual.\n\n2. **Vinegar and Water Soak:**\n   - Mix one part white vinegar with one part water.\n   - Soak the stained area in this solution for 30 minutes.\n   - Scrub gently with a soft brush, then launder the shirt with your regular detergent.\n\n3. **Lemon Juice and Baking Soda:**\n   - Apply lemon juice directly to the stain.\n   - Sprinkle a small amount of baking soda on top.\n   - Use a soft brush to gently scrub the area.\n   - Let it sit for about 15 minutes before rinsing and washing the shirt.\n\n4. **Hydrogen Peroxide Solution:**\n   - Mix one part hydrogen peroxide with one part water (test on an inconspicuous area first to ensure colorfastness).\n   - Apply the solution to the stain and let it sit for about 20 minutes.\n   - Rinse thoroughly with cold water and then launder as usual.\n\n5. **Aspirin and Water Paste:**\n   - Crush a few aspirin tablets and mix with a little water to form a paste.\n   - Apply the paste to the stained area and let it sit for an hour.\n   - Rinse with cold water and wash the shirt.\n\n6. **Commercial Stain Removers:**\n   - Use an enzyme-based stain remover or a product specifically designed for underarm stains.\n   - Follow the instructions on the packaging for best results.\n\nRemember to always check the care label on your garment before using these methods, and spot-test any cleaning solution on an inconspicuous area of the fabric to ensure it doesn\u2019t cause any discoloration or damage. Additionally, avoid using hot water as it can set the stains. If the stains persist, you might need to repeat the process or try a different method.",
